%N A391815 Decimal expansion of the constant x that satisfies x = Sum_{n>=0} 1/2^floor(n*x).
%C A391815 The rational approximation x ~ 7554425181395669/4503599627370495 is accurate to many thousands of digits.
%C A391815 A "devil's staircase" type of constant with large partial quotients in its continued fraction expansion. See MathWorld link for more information.
%H A391815 Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, <a href="https://mathworld.wolfram.com/DevilsStaircase.html">Devil's Staircase</a>.
%F A391815 The constant x may be calculated using the following formulas.
%F A391815 (1) x = 1 + Sum_{n>=1} 1 / 2^floor(n*x).
%F A391815 (2) x = 1 + Sum_{n>=1} floor(n/x) / 2^n.
%F A391815 (3) x = 2 - Sum_{n>=1} 1 / 2^floor(n*x/(x-1)).
%F A391815 (4) x = 2 - Sum_{n>=1} floor(n*(x-1)/x) / 2^n.
%e A391815 x = 1.677419354838709670256625647579633632627970647...
%e A391815 The continued fraction begins (next term is too large to show)
%e A391815 x = [1; 1, 2, 10, 145277407334532, ...]
%e A391815 giving the rational approximation
%e A391815 x ~ 1 + 1/(1 + 1/(2 + 1/(10 + 1/145277407334532))), or
%e A391815 x ~ 7554425181395669/4503599627370495.
%e A391815 RELATED SEQUENCES.
%e A391815 A related Beatty sequence A391809 is
%e A391815 [1, 3, 5, 6, 8, 10, 11, 13, 15, 16, 18, 20, 21, ..., floor(n*x), ...],
%e A391815 where x = 1 + 1/2^1 + 1/2^3 + 1/2^5 + 1/2^6 + 1/2^8 + 1/2^10 + 1/2^11 + 1/2^13 + 1/2^15 + 1/2^16 + 1/2^18 + 1/2^20 + 1/2^21 + ... + 1/2^floor(n*x) + ...
%e A391815 A slower way to calculate x uses the numerators given by
%e A391815 [0, 1, 1, 2, 2, 3, 4, 4, 5, 5, 6, 7, 7, 8, 8, 9, ..., floor(n/x), ...],
